<div id="review_476577947" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/476577947" />
    <a title="Kimberley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15438676-kimberley"><img alt="Kimberley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1557332653p2/15438676.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/476577947?book_show_action=true">Dec 12, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kimberley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kimberley" href="/user/show/15438676-kimberley">Kimberley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15438676-kimberley?shelf=addictive">addictive</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15438676-kimberley?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15438676-kimberley?shelf=books-to-own">books-to-own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer476577947" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14582547944358959493">Crystal Promise was on my bookshelf for a month or so, waiting for me to finish up the other novels I had on my (long) list of &quot;to reads&quot; that tend to take up much of my living space. When I finally did get to it, I didn&apos;t have any expectations as I knew that James Funfer was a new author, and to be honest--the back cover of the book didn&apos;t tell me very much about the plot.<br/><br/>In hindsight, I should have read Crystal Promise immediately. I enjoyed it more than I could have anticipated.<br/><br/>Though Crystal</span>
  <span id="freeText14582547944358959493" style="display:none">Crystal Promise was on my bookshelf for a month or so, waiting for me to finish up the other novels I had on my (long) list of "to reads" that tend to take up much of my living space. When I finally did get to it, I didn't have any expectations as I knew that James Funfer was a new author, and to be honest--the back cover of the book didn't tell me very much about the plot.<br /><br />In hindsight, I should have read Crystal Promise immediately. I enjoyed it more than I could have anticipated.<br /><br />Though Crystal Promise was not written with the intention of falling under the "young adult" fiction category, it certainly does have elements that make that genre so addictive. The narrative follows four young teenagers in their first years of finishing (high) school in the country of Novem. The story is full of love and angst that both adults and teenagers can relate with. The somewhat dramatic storyline is nicely complimented by a well constructed history of Novem (based on 1930's Italy) as well as tear inducing letters corresponded between two young lovers during Novem's wartime.<br /><br />I would highly recommend this book, accompanied by a nice cup of tea and wooly socks.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14582547944358959493" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


